            "bio": "In an age of \"self-made\" men, no American rose more dramatically from humble origins to national and international distinction than Frederick Douglass. During his time in Baltimore, Frederick Douglass \"sought my own employment, made my own contracts, and collected my own earnings.\" Compared to conditions on the plantation, he concluded, \"I was really well off.\" Douglass hastened to add, however, that his favored treatment in no way lessened his desire for freedom—\"it was slavery, not its mere incidents, that I hated.\" Slaveowners employed a variety of means in their attempts to maintain order and discipline among their human property and persuade them to labor productively. Douglass was the son of a slave mother and an unidentified white man, possibly his owner.",
