      "chapterId": "chapter11",
      "type": "Term",
      "front": "\"Cotton is King\"",
      "back": "Cotton is king.\" TABLE 11.1 Growth of the Slave Population The foundation of the Old South's economy, slavery powerfully shaped race relations, politics, religion, and the law. The Cotton Kingdom could not have arisen without the internal slave trade, and the economies of older states like Virginia came increasingly to rely on the sale of slaves. As the domestic slave trade expanded with the rise of the Cotton Kingdom, about one slave marriage in three in slave-selling states like Virginia was broken by sale.",
