      "front": "Free Blacks in the Old South",
      "back": "Some blacks, free and slave, had taken part in the Great Awakening of the colonial era, and even more were swept into the South's Baptist and Methodist churches during the religious revivals of the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. In the Lower South, fugitives tended to head for cities like New Orleans or Charleston, where they hoped to hide \"in plain sight\" among the growing communities of free blacks. Very few free blacks (around 37,000 persons, or less than 2 percent of the area's black population) lived in the Lower South in 1860.",
